                           How to install game?
                           --------------------

                        Installation on floppy disk

        Format  one  floppy  disk  in  Amiga  DOS  format,  using some disk
formatting  utility.  Disk must be named "SW2" (without quotes) or the game
won't  work.   Make  sure that disk is read/write errors free.  Now, unpack
LHA archive content to this disk.

        Now,  make  sure  that  the  game disk is in internal drive.  Enter
Amiga  CLI,  or  Amiga  Shell  (if  you  are  not  already  in it) and type
following:   "sw2:install  df0:"  (no  quotes!) and press Enter.

        This  will  install  bootblock  to game disk, and make it bootable.
This  is  not  needed if you have for example used XCopy for formatting and
selected  some  bootable bootblock for formatting procedure.  Also, you may
install any of custom bootblocks, (which usually have install option within
themselves) like bootblock virus killers etc.

        If  you have done all correctly, you have now your Spherical Worlds
DEMO  disk ready for playing and you may reboot your machine from that disk
to start game.
___________________________________________________________________________

                         Installation on hard disk

        Make  a directory of your choice somewhere on your hard disk.  Then
unpack  LHA  archive  content  to  that  directory,  and you have completed
installation.

        To  start  the  game,  just enter game directory from Workbench and
double  click  on "SphericalWorlds" icon.  Note, that you must have about 1
Mb of free memory to start game from Workbench.

        Game  will  work from hard disk, if you have A1200, A3000 or A4000.
If you have, for example, A500 with hard disk, you might have problems with
hard  disk  install, because of kickstart 1.3 differences to kickstart 2.0,
but everything should work fine anyway.  If you fail to install the game on
hard  disk,  follow  installation  procedure for floppy disk and you should
have no troubles then.

